social_posts.post_text: thinking about the time I took my teta to the MLK @dcpubliclibrary to see my work, and she ended up eagerly watching short docu-videos about Home Rule. thinking about what else DC could lose. thinking about how the US citizenship test doesn’t ask any questions about civil rights or social change beyond Susan B. Anthony. thinking about how much fighting organizers have done to get to this point, and how much is ahead.

trans folks, i love you and i’m with you. when abortion bans were re-introduced last year, it put bodily autonomy on the line for everyone, and here we are with record numbers of anti-trans and anti-lgbtqia+ legislation introduced across the country. i made this photo at @dcdykemarch 2022 where the theme was Bans off Our Bodies. the sentiment still stands. you can’t disappear trans people - they are part of our past and will be part of our future. 🏳️‍⚧️💖

extremely proud to share that Maman & Me, the first full cookbook I’ve photographed, will be released October 24 2023 and is available for pre-order now! if you know me irl, you’ll already know that this is a dream come true. eternally grateful to the incredible duo of @royashariat and @gitajoons for allowing me to contribute to this labor of love. the warmth and joy in these pages is just unparalleled because each story and recipe is a reflection of their family and their home. couldn’t have asked for a better team and that includes @laduelala! link in bio or at mamaandme.com, follow @mamanandme 🌿🍮✨

social_posts.post_text:
haus of bambi and Farrah Skeiky are thrilled to announce a new photo exhibition titled Survive, Glamorously: Images of Drag in the District! This 10 day show, May 3-13 at the gallery at Ron David Studio in Union Market, bears witness to the radical, diverse, and thriving scene that has grown in contradiction to the clean-cut perceptions of Washington, DC. We can’t wait to share these photographs by Cassidy DuHon, Keylimehi, Koto Langa, and Farrah Skeiky with you. 

Join us May 3 for our official opening reception sponsored by Topo Chico!

•
•
•
#queerphotography #photoexhibit #dcphotography #dcevents #queerdc #dragphotography #dragking #dragqueen #drag #dcdrag #DC #queerart #queer #gallery #dcgallery

last month we made kimchi from scratch for the first time. i love kimchi of all kinds but making it at home seemed intimidating! we used @milkimchi’s recipe via @seriouseats, and added in some asian pear and apple for sweetness. it’s been part of whatever iftar plate i’ve put together for the past month, most notably in a steaming pot of sundubu-jjigae. projects like this make me feel grounded, and make our place feel like home ❣️🥬🌶️

new e-commerce work for @unclechipscookies, who offers so much more than cookies! still in a love/hate relationship with gluten (one of longing and yearning) but there’s truly something for everyone here.

eid mubarak, family! here are a few recents for @fryerschicken, where the chicken is always halal, and where the iftar platter includes a pistachio date milkshake 🍗🍨🌙 was this past month about more than food? of course. but whatever you got out of it, whatever challenges you met, i hope you’re celebrating with community, good food, and giving zakat generously.

recent work + outtakes for @washingtonpost for a great story on trailblazing Black American women distance runners. It was an honor to work with two legends for this story. Marilyn Bevans, 73, was the first American-born Black woman to complete the Boston Marathon in 1975, placing fourth. A two-time Maryland Marathon winner, she now coaches high school cross-country and track in Baltimore County. Alisa Harvey, 57, still holds records she set at Thomas Jefferson High School in the 1980s as the first Black woman cross country runner in the school’s history. Harvey went on to compete in the 2000 Olympic Marathon Trials. full story by Kelyn Soong. thanks for the call @mayanmvalentine!

my latest for @smithsonianmagazine dives into daguerreotypes and photographic jewelry made by the earliest known African American photographers, namely Glenalvin Goodridge of York, PA, James P. Ball of Cincinnati, OH, and Augustus Washington of Hartford, CT. these photographers were making portraits of Black and white clients alike in the 19th century. the addition of these daguerreotypes, tintypes, brooches, hair bands, and more means this collection at the Smithsonian American Art Museum is the largest of its kind. story by Richard Grant. thanks @donny_bajohr for the call! link in bio 📷🎞️🧤

the national march on washington for palestine, november 4 2023 🍉 as a non-palestinian, it is not my place to lose hope. but when i do feel myself slipping in that direction, i remember that this was the largest march in solidarity with palestine in US history. i remember the warmth of community. 

this struggle is not new. we have known it for over 75 years. generations of families have been shaped by displacement, personal loss, trauma, identity erasure. every palestinian has stories of enduring casual and pointed cruelty. myself and most of my lebanese family are not strangers to this either. my experiences in the 2006 war left me traumatized as a teen, and i have now been watching that trauma on my screen for 58 days. 

prior to october 7, there was not peace. there was an amount of palestinian death and suffering that was palatable to most of the world. there was a standard cruelty meant to make everyday life miserable; to break the spirit and force an oppressed group to accept this life. do not mistake the status quo with peace. 

15000+ killed, over 6000 of them children. 50+ journalists killed in targeted attacks. if you think this has nothing to do with you: our tax dollars are funding this while americans rely on gofundme campaigns to get out of medical debt, and flint still doesn’t have clean water. 

ceasefire now. end the siege on gaza, and free palestine. and while we’re at it, free congo and sudan. it should not be controversial to want freedom for oppressed people. 🇵🇸🇨🇩🇸🇩

my favorite way to behold my grandparents and parents is in perfectly ordinary moments of softness and ease. i’ve typed and re-typed many paragraphs to help narrate these photos but they’re all too long. so i’ll just say this: every generation of my family has exhibited incredible strength to survive, and all i want for them is ease. generations of us have been defined by our endurance. we’ve faced war and hardship in Lebanon, in Sierra Leone, in other places we’ve made home. 

I’m proud to come from strong people but I wish they never had to endure so much pain. I love where I come from but sometimes it feels like the rest of the world gains more from willfully misunderstanding us and there’s so much loneliness in that intentional ignorance. and I know many Arabs and Muslims share this sentiment, especially as we watch Palestinians persevere through suffering. all i want for them is that same soft life and ease.

Ride for Palestine on 1.7.2024 🛹 in which a group of cyclists, skateboarders and roller skaters led by @native_women_ride rode from malcolm x park to freedom plaza last weekend to continue awareness of and support for palestine. important words were shared by a few folks and @fairouzsoprano brought us all to tears with an opera performance. it’s been nearly 100 days of relentless killing and displacement. this is not the time to give up. please keep pushing!
